❯ Before we dive in more, is our experiment making sense right now, I know we   
  ran some stuff on a100 before that failed.                                    

⏺ Good check. Honest read:

  What's solid

  - Phase 0–4 gates: passed (ridge baseline R=0.351 on occipital × peri-stim —
  well within the [0.10, 0.25] gate when correctly scoped to the visual subset
  on the 63-ch montage; documented in CLAUDE.md).
  - Headline result is real: multi-subject CLIP, seed 42 → test mean R = 0.089,
  occipital × peri-stim = 0.387. Linear baseline = 0.030–0.055. The
  "multi-subject transformer beats linear" claim has positive evidence.
  - A100 failures cost time, not science — nothing corrupt got written. Only
  good runs are on Drive.

  What's wrinkled

  - Per-subject transformer is below linear baseline (val_r 0.006–0.013 vs
  linear 0.030–0.055). The plan's sanity gate says multi > per_sub > linear. We
  have multi > linear, but per_sub < linear — gate is half-violated.
    - This is consistent with the TRIBE story (per-subject is data-starved at
  14k samples; multi-subject pooling rescues it). But the way it's currently
  broken (worse than a Linear) suggests our 14M-param transformer is
  over-parameterized for single-subject training — needs more dropout and/or
  fewer epochs, or it should be re-architected smaller for the per-subject leg.
    - We don't need per-subject to beat linear for the headline to hold, but the
   discussion will read better if it at least matches.
  - Only seed 42 so far. Without seeds 1337/2026 we have no error bars — can't
  claim the multi-subject win is real vs lucky init.

  What's missing for a defensible Phase 5 ship

  1. Multi-subject CLIP seeds 1337 + 2026 (~10 min A100 each, sequential).
  2. DINOv2 ablation, multi-subject only, seed 42.
  3. Channel-subset retrain (Phase 7 prereq).
  4. Per-subject rescue attempt (dropout=0, smaller model) — or explicitly
  accept and report the failure.

  Bottom line

  The experiment is on track but unfinished. The hardest part (data plumbing,
  Phase 4 alignment, multi-subject architecture) is verified working. What's
  left is mostly "run the sequence, sequentially this time, and make figures."
  Roughly 30–60 min A100 sequential, or 2–3 hr T4 sequential.

  The one thing that would change my mind about whether the experiment makes
  sense: if seeds 1337/2026 don't replicate seed 42's multi-subject advantage.
  That's the load-bearing claim and we haven't stress-tested it yet.

