  What's done

  Phase 5 (TS2 training, all on A100, sequential):
  - Linear baseline: R = 0.042 ± 0.008
  - Per-subject (rescue config): R = 0.039 ± 0.017 — ties linear, expected per
  TRIBE's data-starvation hypothesis
  - Multi-subject CLIP, 3 seeds: R = 0.091 ± 0.015 — replicates tightly,
  p<<0.001 vs linear
  - Multi-subject DINOv2: R = 0.068 (clean ablation: CLIP > DINOv2)
  - Multi-subject CLIP, 32-ch subset (the transfer-ready model): R = 0.134 ±
  0.018

  Phase 6 figures: headline_boxplot.{png,pdf}, channel_time_heatmap.png,
  embedding_ablation.png, all_results.csv (80 rows).

  Phase 7 (Alljoined cross-hardware transfer, T4, 5 subjects):
  - Scratch ridge: posterior R = 0.007 ± 0.008
  - Variant A (zero-shot, null pathway): 0.022 ± 0.021 (n.s.)
  - Variant B (subject-block FT, frozen encoder): 0.030 ± 0.014, p = 0.034 — 4×
  scratch ridge
  - Variant C (full FT 1 epoch): 0.024 ± 0.025 (n.s., high variance)

  Phase 8: Five-page Markdown report at report/CEREBRO_report.md (1733 words)
  with all numbers, figures referenced, methods, limitations, future work.

  What got fixed along the way

  - Channel intersection was originally guessed from the arxiv paper (28 ch);
  verified from actual Alljoined sub-01 ch_names it's 32 ch — all of Alljoined ⊂
   BioSemi 64. Phase 5e was retrained on the corrected list.
  - Per-subject transformer was failing badly with full architecture; rescue
  config (d_model=192, n_layers=2, dropout=0.3) brought it to parity with linear
   baseline.
  - A100 parallel-launch deadlock lesson is now codified in CLAUDE.md as a hard
  sequential rule.

  Total Drive: ~75 GB. All artifacts persist across sessions.

